It symbolizes the transient nature of life, as its beautiful blooms are short-lived, reflecting the Buddhist concept of impermanence. Historically, sakura has been celebrated in Japanese literature, poetry, and art for centuries, representing renewal and the fleeting beauty of life.

The annual celebration of cherry blossoms, known as Hanami, involves gathering with family and friends to view and appreciate the blossoms' beauty. This tradition dates back to the Nara period (710-794) and became popular during the Heian period (794-1185). During Hanami, people often have picnics under the blooming trees, enjoying food, drinks, and company while reflecting on the beauty and fleeting nature of life.
